{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646888"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:37:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:37:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18213"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18213","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18213"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.3,0.05,0.05,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10927"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77626"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10927"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18213"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63139"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5290"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25398"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25402"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77626"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EJanus kinase inhibitors are a class of medications used in the treatment of various autoimmune diseases. They work by interfering with the Janus kinase signalling pathway, which plays a role in the immune response.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about Janus kinase inhibitors is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["They are primarily excreted unchanged in the urine","They enhance the immune response","They are safe to use in severe renal impairment without dose adjustment","They are only used in the treatment of cancer","They increase the risk of infection"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EJanus kinase inhibitors, such as baricitinib and tofacitinib, work by modulating the immune system, which can lead to an \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased risk of infection\u003C/strong\u003E. This is due to their immunosuppressive effects, which can make patients more susceptible to infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey are primarily excreted unchanged in the urine\u003C/strong\u003E - Janus kinase inhibitors are metabolised by the liver and excreted by the kidneys, often requiring dose adjustments in renal impairment.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey enhance the immune response\u003C/strong\u003E - These drugs suppress the immune response to treat autoimmune conditions.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey are safe to use in severe renal impairment without dose adjustment\u003C/strong\u003E - Dose adjustments are often necessary in patients with renal impairment.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThey are only used in the treatment of cancer\u003C/strong\u003E - While they have applications in cancer, they are primarily used for autoimmune diseases like rheumatoid arthritis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Janus kinase inhibitors are used to treat autoimmune diseases by modulating the immune response.","These inhibitors can increase the risk of infections due to their immunosuppressive effects.","Janus kinase inhibitors are metabolised by the liver and excreted by the kidneys, requiring dose adjustments in renal impairment."],"references":["Padda IS, Goyal A. Leflunomide. 2023 Jun 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491731","Tian H, Cronstein BN. Understanding the mechanisms of action of methotrexate: implications for the treatment of rheumatoid arthritis. Bull NYU Hosp Jt Dis. 2007;65(3):168-73. PMID: 17922664","Waller, D. G., \u0026 Hitchings, A. W. (2021). Medical Pharmacology and Therapeutics E-Book: Medical Pharmacology and Therapeutics E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Tashjian, A. H., \u0026 Armstrong, E. J. (2011). Principles of pharmacology: the pathophysiologic basis of drug therapy. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Queremel Milani DA, Davis DD. Pain Management Medications. 2023 Jul 3. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32809527","Taylor PC, Choy E, Baraliakos X, Szekanecz Z, Xavier RM, Isaacs JD, Strengholt S, Parmentier JM, Lippe R, Tanaka Y. Differential properties of Janus kinase inhibitors in the treatment of immune-mediated inflammatory diseases. Rheumatology (Oxford). 2024 Feb 1;63(2):298-308. doi: 10.1093/rheumatology/kead448. PMID: 37624925; PMCID: PMC10836981.","Cinats A, Heck E, Robertson L. Janus Kinase Inhibitors: A Review of Their Emerging Applications in Dermatology. Skin Therapy Lett. 2018 May;23(3):5-9. PMID: 29772037."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63139"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18213"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63139"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T20:42:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T20:42:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10927"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77626"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nul